
Prototype Design Pattern ek creational pattern hai jo kehta hai:
existing object ko clone karke naya object banao, instead of creating from scratch.


“Prototype pattern me hum object creation ke liye constructor use nahi karte, balki existing object ko clone karte hain, jo performance improve karta hai especially jab object creation costly ho.”

Simple line:
👉 “Create by copying, not by constructing”

Real Problem (kyun use hota hai?)
User u1 = new User("Manu", "Noida", heavyData);

isme:
DB call ho sakta hai
heavy processing ho sakti hai
object banana expensive ho sakta hai

Ab agar same type ke aur 100 object chahiye?
❌ baar-baar new → costly
✔ ek bana → uski copy bana lo

Flow (step-by-step logic)
Step 1: Class cloneable banegi
class User implements Cloneable

Step 2: clone() method override karte hain
@Override
protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
    return super.clone();
}

Step 3: Object copy karo
User u2 = (User) u1.clone();

Rules (ye yaad hone chahiye)
Class ko Cloneable interface implement karna hoga
clone() method override karna hoga
Object copy banega, constructor call nahi hota
Exception handle karna padta hai (CloneNotSupportedException)


Types (ye interviewer ko impress karega)
1. Shallow Copy = sirf reference copy hota hai
2. Deep Copy = poora object graph copy hota hai


Features
Fast object creation
Constructor bypass hota hai
Complex object cloning possible
Runtime pe object create kar sakte ho

Advantages

✔ Performance fast (heavy object reuse)
✔ Less code for object creation
✔ Complex object easily duplicate
✔ Runtime flexibility

Disadvantages (real truth)

❌ Deep copy banana complex hota hai
❌ Cloneable ka design Java me flawed mana jata hai
❌ Hidden bugs (reference sharing issue)
❌ Debugging tough ho jata hai


Real-world Use Cases
Game development (same enemy copy)
Object templates
Cache objects
Spring me prototype scope beans